observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the appropriate journal entries relative to the unrecorded liability and the erroneous classification of transactions amounting to ₱16,850.00 and ₱0.877 million, respectively. Accordingly, working paper adjustment entries shall be prepared for the restatement of the affected accounts to present the correct CY 2024 restated figures in the preparation of the CY 2025 comparative FS;
Ensure that goods and services that have been delivered or rendered as at year end be properly recorded as liabilities. Relative to this, require, as year-end cut-off procedures, the Municipal General Services Office to forward to the Municipal Accounting Office all claims for delivered goods and services for the proper recognition of AP on the related transactions;
Investigate the nature and validity of the ₱38,146.08 long outstanding AP. Relative to this, Management shall coordinate with the identified supplier. The residual amount after reconciliation shall be reverted to the unappropriated surplus; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to properly disclose in the NFS the contingent liability arising from the undelivered POs at year-end to ensure the fair presentation of the FS.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Immediately record the disbursements of ₱7.139 million from the account “Due to LGUs” and recognize the “Other Deferred Credits” of the same amount in accordance with the accrual basis of accounting prescribed under IPSAS 1 to reflect the actual utilization of funds;
Conduct a comprehensive review of the existing balances of the accounts “Due from LGUs” and “Due to NGAs,” and reconstruct a detailed monitoring report and/or subsidiary ledgers, disaggregated by specific agency, transaction, and fund source, to ensure traceability, accuracy, and completeness of recorded liabilities;
Establish and implement a regular monitoring and reconciliation process between the general ledger and subsidiary ledgers to validate the existence, accuracy, and aging of outstanding payables, and to promptly identify and resolve any discrepancies;
Reclassify the amount of ₱22,675.94 from the “Due to NGAs” account to the appropriate liability account, “Guaranty/Security Deposit Payable.” Also, identify the contractor who made the payment and verify whether the amount is still valid and outstanding or if it is already due for refund or forfeiture based on the terms and conditions of the contract;
Strictly adhere to Sections 4.6 and 4.9 of COA Circular No. 94-013 by ensuring the preparation of Liquidation Reports on a monthly basis for all received funds, regardless of whether transactions have occurred, and promptly submit within the prescribed period to this Office and the respective Source Agencies. Also, indicate the date of preparation, and proper report number in all Liquidation Reports to ensure completeness, traceability, and audit trail integrity. Relative thereto, assign personnel to monitor the timely submission of the same; and
Require the personnel in-charge in the review and monitoring of commitments and agreements with partner-agencies to clearly specify project implementation timelines, including the start date, completion date, and reporting deadlines, to prevent delays and promote efficient fund utilization. Additionally, ensure that the date of signing by both parties is explicitly indicated in the MOA and notarized. A clear copy of the signed MOA shall be submitted to this Office for proper monitoring and reference.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accounting Office to:
Conduct a thorough review on the outstanding “Guaranty/Security Deposits Payable” account to determine the nature and validity of the balances;
Establish and implement regular monitoring and reconciliation procedures to promptly identify and address long-outstanding balances;
Prepare the necessary JEV to correct the erroneous recording of the proceeds from sale bid documents amounting to ₱5,000.00 by debiting “Guaranty/Security Deposit Payable” and crediting “Trust Liabilities”;
Coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer’s Office to locate and retrieve the archived documents that were placed in storage during the office relocation. If necessary, establish a temporary task force or team dedicated to retrieving and finding these records; and
Based on any available historical records (e.g., disbursement vouchers, journal entries, or OR, identify the names of the suppliers/contractors who made the security/guaranty deposits in prior years and assess whether such amounts warrant refund or write-off in accordance with applicable laws, rules, and regulations. Henceforth, ensure the information, such as name of supplier/contractor, OR number, the date of deposit, validity of deposit among others, are readily available for ease of monitoring; and
Instruct the Municipal Accounting Office and Municipal Treasury Office to formally notify and coordinate with suppliers and contractors with valid claims, requesting them to submit the necessary documents for the prompt processing and release of their warranty and retention deposits.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to determine the cost of the issued inventories covered by the 52 SSMIs as noted above and prepare the appropriate accounting entries thereon;
Revisit the supply and property management system of the agency and require the unit supply officers to render report as regards the issuances and consumption of the inventories within their respective offices to be submitted timely to the GSO/Municipal Treasurer for checking and consolidation prior to submission to Municipal Accountant for proper recording;
Henceforth, instruct the GSO-Designate and Inspectorate team, as applicable, to timely provide the Municipal Accountant the documents such as Acceptance and Inspection Report (AIR), Purchase Order and Delivery Receipts, for every duly delivered item, in whole or part. Accordingly, the Municipal Accountant shall prepare an entry to recognize the corresponding asset and liability account with its equivalent amount per Purchase Orders/Contracts; and
Require the proper utilization of the stock cards at the office level in the monitoring of supplies and materials.

We recommended that Management:
Consider reorganizing the Inventory Committee by creating sub-committees on a “per account title” basis with counterparts from the Accounting Office. Actual physical count, investigation of differences and reconciliation of balances shall be conducted by the sub-committees to be accomplished within a specific timeline to be set. Accordingly, adjust the appropriate records as warranted and submit a revised RPCPPE based on the reconciliations made;
Henceforth, schedule the annual physical count during the current year. Relative to this, strict monitoring and control shall be made for the issuances and procurement from the actual date of the count to the December 31 cut-off date for inclusion in the final report to be submitted on or before January 31 of the ensuing year;
Require the Municipal Accounting Office and Municipal General Services office to reconcile the noted variance amounting to ₱2,526,003.37 to enhance fair presentation of the PPE accounts in the financial statements;
Require the Inventory Committee in coordination with the concerned offices and the Accounting Office to analyze the nature of the items included in the RPCPPE with a total cost of ₱1,301,000.00 and classify them according to the appropriate and specific PPE class for correctness of report submissions;
Create and direct the Agency’s disposal committee to initiate the disposal procedures for the unserviceable property identified costing ₱4,940,787.10 which shall be reported in the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP);
Direct the Municipal General Service Office to observe the proper inventory taking, naming and property card monitoring of all procured, donated and transferred PPE where the LGU-Sabtang is the rightful owner as prescribed in Chapter 7 of MNGAS-LGUs. Relative to this, all PPE movements (additions/deductions) shall be promptly communicated with the Accounting Office for proper recording/adjustments in the books;
Direct the Municipal Accounting Office to maintain Ledger Cards for each category of PPE; and
Prioritize the completion of the documentary and procedural requirements of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances and furnish the Audit Team with the necessary documentation.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Review the status of the accounts particularly those that are long outstanding for an undetermined period and observe the guidelines and procedures on the write-off of Dormant Payable accounts as prescribed in COA Circular 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016;
Investigate the exact source of the outstanding balances with no available information, cause the immediate reconciliation of unliquidated fund transfers from the NGAs, and prepare adjusting entries as appropriate;
Reclassify the payables due to the PGB totaling ₱4,050,201.64 from the “Due to NGAs” account to the “Due to LGUs” account; and
Promptly determine the causes of the negative balances in the Due to NGAs account. Accordingly, Management shall coordinate with the SAs for the reconciliation of the balances  and effect the necessary adjusting entries, as warranted.

We recommended that Management:
Provide an explanation/justification why the ₱1,250,000.00 representing the, of ₱960,484.66 in cash and ₱289,515.34 in-kind should not be disallowed in audit in view of the absence of express authority granted to the Municipal Mayor by the Sangguniang Bayan of LGU-Sabtang to enter into a Tripartite MOA/sub-project agreement with the DSWD and Barangay Sinakan;
Henceforth, ensure that the Municipal Mayor is duly authorized to represent the LGU in all agreements and contracts, as applicable in the circumstances;
Provide an explanation/justification why the in-kind LCC shall not be disallowed on account of Management’s failure to obtain the consent of the DSWD on the change of the original object of the agreement that is provision of equipment and various materials and tools with a total value of ₱289,515.34;
Submit a Certification from the General Services Officer/Property Custodian that the equipment committed by the Agency were unserviceable/
non-functional during the implementation of the sub-project;
Obtain, if warranted, the approval of the DSWD on the conversion of the in-kind LCC, from provision of equipment and various materials and tools to 114.89 cubic meters excavated sand; Otherwise, the original items, as committed, shall be delivered by the Agency to avoid exposure to risks of non-compliance and breach of agreement;
Obtain proof that the 114.89 cubic meters excavated sand valued at ₱289,515.34 effectively reduced the amount due to the contractor of the project; and
Provide an explanation/justification why the in-kind LCC, 114.89 cubic 
meters excavated sand with a total value of ₱289,515.34, shall not be disallowed on account of the apparent violation of the laws and regulations prohibiting quarrying in the Province of Batanes. Henceforth, ensure that environmental rules and regulations are strictly observed and implemented by the Municipality.

We recommended that Management:
Provide an explanation/justification why Management did not initiate actions against the contractor to enforce the performance of its obligation on account of the delayed completion of the Phase I of the project;
Identify the most appropriate course of action to ensure the completion of the project which includes the possible termination of the contract as justified by the circumstances. Should Management opt to terminate the same, the procedures set out in Annex I of the Updated 2016 Revised IRR. shall be strictly followed; and
Ensure that the applicable calibrated actions in response to delays in the implementation of infrastructure projects provided GPPB  Circular No. 03-2019 dated March 08, 2019 are performed specifically when the negative slippage reaches 5%, 10% or 15%;
Henceforth, require the Municipal Engineer to strictly monitor the implementation of the Agency’s programs, projects and activities and ensure the protection of government interest by availing of the remedies available and allowed by the Procurement Law and other regulations;
Intensify the coordination and monitoring of commitments made by  the partner agencies to facilitate the provision of the needed operational support; and
Assess the condition of the facility, the  equipment and items therein and ensure the preservation of the building and all equipment and items thereon. Accordingly, repair works shall be undertaken prior to the commencement of its operations.

We recommended that Management:
Continue to monitor the implementation of the PPAs to attain 100% completion;
Ensure that all PPAs are meticulously and judiciously planned by rigidly screening PPAs to be funded out of the 20% DF especially during the preparation of budget proposal. Accordingly, require the implementing offices to propose projects that are well-planned and procurement-and implementation-ready;
Require the BAC and the Municipal Planning and Development Office (MPDO) to properly plan all its procurement activities, particularly the procurement of infrastructure projects taking into consideration the period of implementation to avoid delays and suspensions;
Recommend to the MPDC, in collaboration with the relevant implementing offices and in coordination with the BAC, to conduct regular reviews of project implementation. This will facilitate the identification of projects that may not be feasibly implemented within the year, allowing for proactive measures and strategies to enhance fund utilization;
Direct the implementing offices to refrain from proposing projects that are fully composed of labor cost which is contrary to the intent of the Local Government Code. Accordingly, require the reviewing bodies, the Local Finance Committee and the Local Sanggunian, to rigorously evaluate the propriety, composition, accuracy and completeness of each Department’s budget proposals, to ensure that only relevant, responsive and feasible items are to be funded and implemented out of the 20% DF; and
Require the implementing offices, in coordination with Accounting Office, to fast track the preparation of necessary documents for claims that are already due and demandable, thereby increasing the utilization rate of the PPAs as of year-end.

We recommended that Management:
Strengthen needs-based GAD planning by conducting thorough research and analysis and close coordination with stakeholders and other offices within the agency prior to crafting the programs, project and activities (PPAs) included in the GPB;
Utilize the GAD tools available such as HGDG. Relative to this, include within the PPAs the training program on the HGDG or seek assistance of gender analysis specialist/expert to further increase utilization rate and maximize budget allotment at PPA level;
Develop substitute PPAs in case of unforeseen circumstances that may hinder the implementation of the originally planned PPAs included in the GAD Plan and Budget, and strictly follow the process flow of approval and endorsement of the updated GAD Plan and Budget as prescribed under Section C.7 of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA Joint Circular Memorandum No. 2013-01;
Regularly monitor and evaluate the utilization of the GAD funds that would ensure that total reported costs of GAD accomplishments would achieve at least 5% of agency’s total appropriations/approved budget; and
Comply and submit the appropriate documentary requirements in accordance with PCW‐NEDA‐DBM Joint Circular 2013‐01.

We recommended that Management:
Ensure that PPAs funded out of the DRRM funds are well-planned and meticulously reviewed by the LDRRMC. Accordingly, intensive planning and coordination with stakeholders and implementing offices shall be conducted prior to the inclusion of PPAs in the LDRRMP and LDRRMFIP;
Require the Municipal Planning and Development Officer together with the concerned implementing offices, in coordination with the Local Finance Committee, to conduct a periodic review and assessment of the financial and physical status of the PPAs to determine on a timely basis the possible declaration of savings, which will be reappropriated for new or existing LDRRM-related PPAs, and formulate catch-up plans for slow-moving PPAs to avoid further delays in the implementation;
Require the implementing office, in coordination with Bids and Awards Committee, to adopt a more dynamic procurement strategy aligned with weather forecasts and historical data on weather patterns in the locality to ensure the sufficiency and immediate availability of LDRRM-related items, when needed. Accordingly, for welfare food items, Management shall endeavor to enter into Framework Agreement with prospective suppliers and “Call-off” may be executed and issued to the winning supplier immediately upon the determination that an item is needed, pursuant to the guidelines under Annex 32 of the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) of Republic Act No. 9184 otherwise known as the Government Procurement Reform Act. With this, lean and just-in-time procurements are achieved and the limited storage facilities of the LGU can be maximized;
Utilize the stock card in the inventory management to ensure that welfare goods are available and in optimal condition when required. Similarly, ensure the timely and proper disposal of nearly expiring goods/items through the identified modality by the LGU, to preclude any wastage of government funds; and
Ensure that all properties of the government are properly safeguarded against deterioration, loss and wastage.

We recommended that Management:
Submit explanation/justification with verifiable basis why disbursements on procurements which were noted as non-compliant with existing procurement law, as mentioned above, should not be suspended/disallowed in post-audit;
Henceforth, require the BAC to submit the proof of validation on the technical, legal and financial capability of all the suppliers together with Mayor’s Permit and proof of PhilGEPs Registration on all purchases made through Alternative Mode of Procurement to support eligibility of suppliers;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursements for the procurement of goods and services are included and updated in the end-user PPMP and Agency APP by requiring a certification to that effect from the Head of the BAC Secretariat, who shall, based on the submissions of the end-user units, validate such fact;
Ensure that all regulatory permits, registrations and licenses are available and up-to-date prior to engaging the services of individuals and businesses. If unavailable, encourage the prospective suppliers to secure permits and comply other registration requirements such as Mayor’s Permit, BIR and PhilGEPS registrations etc., to ensure eligibility in future procurement endeavors with the LGU; and
Carefully review the most appropriate mode of procurement to be undertaken to promote economy of time and resources and protect the Management from possible risks.

We recommended that Management:
include as a priority project the establishment of a room/building which shall serve as the storage facility for procured property and inventories prior to the release to end-user units. Relative to this, Management shall endeavor to maintain a centralized inventory management system;
pending the establishment of a storage room/warehouse, the Municipal Mayor shall designate employees, who shall be properly bonded, to manage the issuance, recording and reporting of inventories in their respective offices;
require the Agency’s Inventory Committee together with the representatives from the end-user units and the Designated GSO to conduct an inventory count on all office supplies that are yet to be consumed as of a cut-off date to be determined by the Committee and prepare a Report on Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) for recording and control purposes. Henceforth, conduct the required physical count and submit to the Auditor the report thereon not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
based on the RPCI prepared, the Municipal Accountant shall prepare an entry to recognize the cost of Inventories at hand and henceforth observe the proper accounting policies and entries in the recording of transactions; and
ensure that all properties of the government are properly safeguarded against deterioration, loss and wastage.

We recommended that Management:
submit explanation/justification with verifiable basis why disbursements on procurements which were noted as non-compliant with existing procurement law, as mentioned above, should not be suspended/disallowed in post-audit;
henceforth, require the BAC to submit the proof of validation on the technical, legal and financial capability of the suppliers together with Mayor’s Permit and proof of PhilGEPS Registration on all purchases made through Alternative Mode of Procurement to support eligibility of suppliers;
henceforth, require the submission of BAC resolution recommending award of contract to the supplier with lowest quotation which complies with the specifications and other terms and conditions stated in the Request for Quotation (RFQ) as additional basis of the Head of Agency to enter into contract with the said supplier;
direct the BAC Secretariat to ensure that posting requirements of RFQ, Notice of Award, Purchase Order/Contract and Notice to Proceed if necessary, on all procurement through shopping with ABC higher than P50,000.00 are complied with and proof thereof are attached to the disbursement voucher to establish correctness of information and reliability of bidding process;
require the end-user and BAC to provide clearly and with certainty the necessary information such as technical specifications, scope of work, and other terms and conditions in the RFQ;
advise the end-user and the BAC to provide an explanation for the use of brand name on the identified transaction. Henceforth, unless it falls within the circumstances for exception provided in Section IV.I, Annex H of the 2016 Revised IRR, refrain from including brand names in  the technical specifications as this is expressly prohibited in the IRR;
direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to withhold the total amount of P24,755.12 from the identified suppliers representing liquidated damages and henceforth strictly monitor the timeliness of deliveries for possible imposition thereof;
direct the Inspection Officer and the Property Officer, based on verifiable evidence, to identify the actual dates of deliveries of the goods with incomplete details in the Purchase Orders(POs) and/or Acceptance and Inspection Reports (AIRs) as identified;
based on the information to be obtained from the Inspection Officer and the Property Officer, the Municipal Accountant shall ascertain on a per PO basis, whether or not delay in the delivery of procured items exists, compute the applicable liquidated damages thereon, as warranted and withhold the same from the future payments to the identified suppliers;
direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursements for the procurement of goods and services are included in the end-user PPMP and Agency APP by requiring a certification to that effect from the Head of the BAC Secretariat, who shall, based on the submissions of the end-user units, validate such fact; and
require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all essential information are provided in the supporting documents to establish the validity and legality of the transactions.

